DATA['2017'] = [{"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/7698.html", "year": "2017", "month": "12", "day": "25", "time": "02-16PM", "comments": [{"id": "entry-7698", "title": "", "date": "Dec . 25th , 2017 02:16 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": " As noted on the blog last Wednesday, instead of an \"ask me anything\" post this week on ecosophia.net, I'll be hosting a \"Magic Monday\" today. What does that mean? It means \"ask me anything about occultism, and I'll post an answer here.\" Since this Monday is a busy day for a lot of people, being sacred to two popular religions -- Christianity on the one hand, and Consumerism on the other -- if comments trickle in on Tuesday et al., I'm not going to be a stickler for the point. <br/><br/><strike>That said, have at it! </strike><br/><br/>***PLEASE NOTE: as of midnight, 26 December 2017, this Magic Monday has packed its tents and gone away. If you have questions you haven't posted yet, please save them for the next Magic Monday on January 1!.***", "metadata": {"mood": "cheerful", "tags": ["ask me anything", "magic monday", "occultism"]}}, {"id": "cmt87314", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 07:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How would you go about formulating a hwptagram ritual to work with planetary energies?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt88594", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 09:24 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, are you working within the Hermetic Golden Dawn tradition or any of its offshoots? If so, you'd want to begin with the LVX signs, then trace a heptagram in the four quarters, then finish with the IAO analysis. The heptagram? You'd take that from the ceiling of the Vault -- look at color plate 6 in the new seventh edition of Regardie's <i>The Golden Dawn</i> for a handy diagram. The points are labeled in Hebrew with their Sephirothic correspondences, so you can take the planetary correspondences from that. <br/><br/>If you're not working within the Hermetic Golden Dawn tradition or one of its offshoots, you can still do the same thing -- the number of groups utterly unrelated to the Golden Dawn that make use of the Lesser Ritual of the Pentagram is pretty impressive -- or you can borrow equivalent symbolism from your own tradition. I'd have to have some idea of what you're working with to be able to make any more constructive suggestions. "}]}, {"id": "cmt87570", "title": "intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-25 08:38 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG<br/><br/>You’ve mentioned in a few places how different magic systems make use of different energy centres/symbolism/techniques/etc because they have different goals. Could you describe the overall intentions which shape such factors in systems you are familiar with? <br/><br/>Also, on the Well of Galabes, I think there is mention about a future post on the drawbacks of the Golden Dawn, which I would be curious to hear more about if an additional question isn’t too greedy. <br/><br/>Merry Magic Monday!<br/>Bewilderness", "replies": [{"id": "cmt88850", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-25 09:39 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a huge issue! Very broadly speaking, the midline of the human body is like the string of a musical instrument -- say, a violin, because it doesn't have any frets built in. Wherever you put your finger on a string, you define a note, and the different scales you can play require different placements of your finger. In the same way, the human energy body resonates with different levels of existence at different points along its midline, and wherever you concentrate, you bring out that resonance. <br/><br/>So if all you want is the particular set of resonances that make you a good martial artist, you concentrate strictly on the point along the midline that's about two finger widths below the navel -- thats the hara or dantien, the energy point used in most East Asian martial arts. If all you want is a certain mode of intuitive clairvoyance, you concentrate on the point between the eyebrows, and so on. If you want a more balanced set of results, you work with a series of points. <br/><br/>Symbols and techniques are the same way. What do you want to achieve? If you want visionary experiences, there's one set of practices; if you want the capacity to move and shape subtle energies, there's another; if you want the kind of transformative experience generally known as \"enlightenment,\" there's another, and so on. All roads emphatically do not lead to the same place, and if you're in New York and want to get to Boston, you don't take the highway headed south. <br/><br/>As for the Golden Dawn, that's actually fairly simple. The rituals of initiation are keyed to the Spheres of the Tree of Life, and that results in a very predictable kind of blowback if you take an initiation for a Sphere you haven't already integrated. The usual problem comes with the Adeptus Minor ritual, since very few people have integrated the Tiphareth level of consciousness; when they take the initiation, unless they can successfully coordinate the influx of energy with their existing state of consciousness -- which does happen, fortunately, but not as often as one would like -- the initiate manifests the Qliphothic side of Tiphareth instead, and becomes an arrogant jerk convinced of his own omniscience.<br/><br/>That's why there are so many people like that in the Golden Dawn scene; it's an unfortunate side effect of the structure of the grades. That's also why Dion Fortune and so many other offshoots of the Golden Dawn tradition scrapped the existing grade structure and replaced it, usually with a system of three degrees not linked to the Tree of Life; you get the same positive effects without the blowback. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt95250", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-26 01:51 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How do druidry and the Golden Dawn compare in terms of the goals of the training?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt96530", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-26 03:23 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on the variety of Druidry we're talking about -- it's a very diverse spiritual movement. Which version of Druidry did you have in mind? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt99346", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-26 04:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Primarily, Druidry as in the Druid Magic Handbook and, secondarily, OBOD.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt107026", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 12:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not familiar with the current OBOD system; in the old correspondence course, it aimed at a general awakening of the subtle body, the sort of thing that makes a good preparation for any kind of general spiritual practice. (There were higher aspects of the work as well, but those aren't public.) AODA's system, which is the basis for the material in <i>The Druid Magic Handbook</i>, is rather more specific: it works with three energy centers, head, heart, and womb, and thus aims primarily at the integration of spiritual, mental, and emotional life in the individual, and secondarily at developing certain specific capacities for perceiving and shaping the life force, which are needed for the modes of Druid work discussed in the book. (I'll save my comments on the Golden Dawn for the comment below.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt114194", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 01:59 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are things like invisibility and animal transformation also possible within AODA's system, or are those not amongst the developed capacities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt114706", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 02:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They're not among the capacities the AODA system develops. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt103698", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-26 01:01 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not originally my question, but I'd like to ask; between the Golden Dawn and the Druidical Order of the Golden Dawn?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt107282", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 12:18 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Same intention, different symbolism. The Golden Dawn tradition in general aims primarily at integrating the lower and higher selves, and secondarily at empowering the initiate to do work on the whole range of inner planes. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt115474", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 02:31 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Continuing from the string simile, what levels of existence and capacities resonate with the five energy centres activated during a Middle Pillar/Central Ray exercise, and what effects does the invocation of the Celtic gods have beyond those achieved by visualising the spheres of light in each place?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt116498", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 04:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Malkuth/Naf center connects the energy body to the telluric current, the subtle energy of the Earth; the Yesod/Ner center awakens the same primary energy currents of the body worked by kundalini yoga, but in a less risky way; the Tiphareth/Muner center activates the creative imagination and the higher aspects of the Personality; the Daath/Iau center, on one plane, activates the magical dimensions of the voice, and on a higher plane facilitates the connection betweeh the Personality and the Individuality; and the Kether/Celi center is the link to the wholly transcendent aspects of the self and facilitates mystical experience. You can find out a good deal more about all of this in Dion Fortune's book <i>The Circuit of Force</i>. <br/><br/>Vibrating divine names or words of power in the centers is crucial to their full awakening. Partly that's because focusing sound on these centers has a potent effect on the etheric aspects of the body; partly it's because the gods and goddesses are real beings who can assist in the work if invoked respectfully!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt118034", "title": "Re: intentions of different magic systems", "date": "2017-12-27 08:59 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks JMG. That was great."}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt87826", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 08:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Regarding breathing in light/CGD I'm having a bit of trouble with the visualization. Not getting the ocean of bright colorless light as much as blobs of translucent jelly, kinda like when you break a glowstick. Tried to go more by feeling instead of visualization which seems to help, but want to make sure that's okay. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt89106", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 09:40 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, it's okay -- in fact, it suggests that you're developing astral clairvoyance, which is a very good thing to have. Keep practicing, and you'll notice that the blobs spread and merge, and eventually you'll get the ocean of light. "}]}, {"id": "cmt88082", "title": "Three-planet problem", "date": "2017-12-25 08:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How do you interpret the effects of closely conjunct stellia in a natal chart?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt89874", "title": "Re: Three-planet problem", "date": "2017-12-25 09:57 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Is the Sun involved? In that case the other planets are combust, and their influences are partly subsumed into that of the Sun. You'd expect in that case that the native would have a hard time differentiating things under the planetary rulerships from his own identity. For example, I have Mercury very close to my natal Sun, so my personal identity is very much wrapped up with my ideas and my thoughts. <br/><br/>If the Sun's not involved, you get the same intermingling without any one planet being dominant. The aspects of the native's life ruled by the planets in the stellium won't be easily separable -- for example, if Mercury and Venus are part of the stellium, the native will have a hard time keeping thinking and feeling separate. The basic rule is that in a conjunction -- and this is true no matter how many planets are part of it -- the planets mingle their identities and influences. "}]}, {"id": "cmt88338", "title": "Alive but \"already gone\"", "date": "2017-12-25 09:21 pm", "user": "quietmagpie", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>A lot of the previous thought about spirits, the will, and death has led me to a question. A number of people in my social circle have had to deal with friends and relatives who are suffering from Alzheimers. One of them described the experience as having to watch their mother die twice, because although she was still technically alive \"she\" was gone. I was reading in the Divine Comedy that Dante meets a number of souls in hell who's bodies were still living on earth and it got me thinking: is it possible for the part of the self that wills beyond simple instinct to pass on while the body is still alive and even speaking and walking?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt90130", "title": "Re: Alive but \"already gone\"", "date": "2017-12-25 10:01 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If there's speaking and walking going on, there's more than simple instinct present, and that means there's still at least some connection between the material body and the personality. In Alzheimer's, as I recall from my days working in nursing homes, there still seems to be some connection until the last voluntary actions stop and you've got an empty shell lying in a bed. "}]}, {"id": "cmt89362", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 09:50 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Violet)<br/><br/>Many thanks for hosting this! In the past few weeks I've spent a goodly amount of time with dice, doing geomantic readings about possible paths I can take in the near term future.  While doing this, I've been noticing that I struggle to imagine  a path, or even a destination.  It's like the future is extra-foggy.<br/><br/>For about 9 years I've practiced different systems of divination, and the last time I had this sort of uncertainty was during the aftermath of the 2008 housing crisis.  I'm concerned that it may be difficult to 'see' into potential futures because of disruptions in the normal flow of emanation from spiritual plane on down, or put differently there is a kind of 'storm' in the anima mundi, or the part of the anima mundi that relates to human groupings. Sometimes of a future imagining has, seemingly led me, to its realization on the physical.  My guess would be that I feel some sort of contraction of possibility in the near term future. My question is: how does one best proceed when the future is murky, and it's hard to even get a good visual?  How does one proceed when the amount of possibility, rather than just desirability or pragmatics, is hard to discern? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt90386", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 10:10 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "How does one best proceed? Very, very carefully! Occult tradition has it that as a society drifts further and further into delusion and dysfunction, one consequence is that the lower astral plane -- the end that resonates with corrupt emotional states, degraded thoughtforms, and the like -- becomes overloaded with energy. That makes it very difficult for ordinary astral functions such as clairvoyance and precognition to operate. (The reason psychic phenomena are so much rarer and weaker today than they were in earlier times, according to the theory, is that the modern era has seen a buildup of static on the lower astral unparalleled since the days of a certain legendary and long-drowned civilization.) That proceeds until the corrupted energies find a way to discharge themselves into matter, usually by way of disasters of various kinds. These become more frequent and damaging until finally the lower astral is reasonably clear. I think you're right that a \"contraction of possibility\" is approaching -- that's a useful phrase, by the way! -- and divination may be of limited use until it passes. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt94738", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 01:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder if such times being particularly unpredictable/'random' makes them harder to divine, but more easily influenced by magic.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt96786", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 03:24 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. I haven't noticed any particular change in the efficacy of my working, but then I don't do a lot on the lower astral. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt101906", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 07:11 am", "user": "yuccaglauca", "content": "I have a clarification question about the lower astral. Does the term \"lower\" here include the meaning \"closer to ether\" that is sometimes used to talk about different densities of astral material, or is this a separate axis of \"lowness?\" <br/><br/>Also, you've recommended good magical practice to cause someone to resonate less with the lower astral. Is this a simple matter of moving away from the lower astral and so not being as involved in it, or does one still need to take care to cultivate better patterns on the lower astral, even while changing focus to higher levels? More clearly, I'm concerned about making sure that nothing is being repressed that will caused the sort of problems that repressed things often do. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt107538", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 12:22 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Lower as in closer to the etheric and physical. The different sublevels of the planes seem to sort out according to something equivalent to density, and the lower astral is denser than the middle and upper astral, with the etheric being denser still. <br/><br/>If you're engaging in regular magical practice, the result isn't to repress the lower astral, it's to attune your astral body to the middle and upper astral -- rather like getting up onto the sidewalk so you don't have to keep walking in the gutter. You're not repressing the muck, you're just not wading in it any more. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt100370", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 05:22 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How local is this phenomenon?  For example, would a clairvoyant who travels beyond the boundaries, material or otherwise, of her delusional and disfunctional society notice a difference in her abilities?  <br/><br/>-Dan Mollo", "replies": [{"id": "cmt107794", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 12:24 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's somewhat localized, by all accounts. You can't get wholly away from it by physical travel, but there's a decrease in its intensity. "}]}, {"id": "cmt102418", "title": "www.ferngladefarm.blogspot.com.au/", "date": "2017-12-26 09:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John Michael,<br/><br/>Sorry to add in a data point here, but I thought you my be interested to know that I am observing that there seems to be a lot more folks in a state of heightened emotions than I have ever previously observed.<br/><br/>I am unfortunately sensitive to such things and it causes me a mild feeling of distress, but living a quiet life up in the mountains provides considerable relief to that aura.<br/><br/>Cheers<br/><br/>Chris", "replies": [{"id": "cmt108050", "title": "Re: www.ferngladefarm.blogspot.com.au/", "date": "2017-12-27 12:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Doesn't surprise me at all. Things seem to be really building toward crisis. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt115730", "title": "Re: www.ferngladefarm.blogspot.com.au/", "date": "2017-12-27 02:46 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I would go so far as to call it a lower-astral psychic hurricane. A friend of mine who is also psychically sensitive and I have been suffering from excruciating and intractable sleep-problems ever since Pluto started transiting within one degree a sensitive point in our charts that we share in a manner of speaking (she has Venus in 18-Aries and I have Mars in 18-Libra). And it's really strange, because the permutations of this issue we each experience parallel with one another exactly (including beginning in earnest when Pluto moved into that one-degree transiting position in the middle of January of last year). Both she and I are watching Pluto move beyond the range of 18-Capricorn this year with our fingers crossed!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt119314", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-28 05:00 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there any way to assist in 'grounding out' this corrupt energy? Standard regular magical practices like banishing and meditation no doubt help an individual navigate these conditions better than most and stop contributing to them, but is there anything that can be done to take some of the sting out of it and ameliorate the disasters occurring on the material plane? I am aware this is a natural phenomenon, and it will proceed and resolve itself in due course, but if there is any way to spare my nearest and dearest some of the worst of it, I would like to try."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt89618", "title": "Communicating with gods.", "date": "2017-12-25 09:55 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "At the moment I am reading Iamblichus and he talks about dreams being a major way of communicating with gods. What methods have you found most successful?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt90642", "title": "Re: Communicating with gods.", "date": "2017-12-25 10:12 pm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never had much luck working with my dreams. Some people find that very effective, but here as so often, different people have different gifts. Myself, I find prayer the most useful method, but that may have a lot to do with a standard Golden Dawn training in the use of the imagination as a means of perception; I pray, and then I listen, and generally there's an answer. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt93458", "title": "Re: Communicating with gods.", "date": "2017-12-26 12:41 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I just finished reading T. L. Luhrmann's _When God Talks Back_ which is about the Vineyard and related new style evangelical churches. The main thing she studied was the way in which they taught prayer as a technique and a skill that required work and practice. I was amazed to learn that these evangelical  Protestants have started using the Spiritual Exercises devised by Ignatius Loyola (founder of the Jesuit Order). These exercises involve concentrating on imagining oneself into Scripture scenes, seeing, touching, hearing, smelling. Luhrmann then devised an experimental study of the effects of different prayer training: passive listening to pink noise, active imagining scenes and a control group that just listened to a taped lecture on Scripture. Really interesting work. <br/><br/>Luhrmann's first work as an anthropologist was among magicians and Witches in England, leading to the book _Persuasions of the Witch's Path_. Warning, the book is quite dense with anthropological terminology that may be fairly opaque to the <br/>outsider. <br/><br/>Rita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt97042", "title": "Re: Communicating with gods.", "date": "2017-12-26 03:25 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting! Yes, I read her first book, skimmed the jargon, and found the accounts of magical groups in England fascinating. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt90898", "title": "Magic Monday Greetings!", "date": "2017-12-25 11:03 pm", "user": "ferngladefarm.blogspot.com.au", "content": "Hi John Michael,<br/><br/>Thanks for this opportunity to ask open questions on occult lore! Your reply over at Ecosophia about the timing of ceremonies has given me much to ponder and consider.<br/><br/>A couple of weeks back we spoke about the perception of time becoming more fluid if the mind opens to the possibility of where country (i.e. the land) has been and where it is going to. As usual that has left my mind with more questions than answers, but I was wondering whether you reckon we are trained to ignore consequences and possibilities and instead focus on abstract concepts, so as to ignore that faculty of the mind? Dunno, but it is a possibility?<br/><br/>Cheers<br/><br/>Chris", "replies": [{"id": "cmt92178", "title": "Re: Magic Monday Greetings!", "date": "2017-12-26 12:16 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's more than a possibility. Education in the modern industrial world is as much a matter of teaching people not to think in certain ways and not to pay attention to certain perceptions as anything else. A fixation on arbitrary abstractions is central to modern education, and I don't think it's accidental; the gap between the world people actually experience and the one that modern ideologies insists people ought to experience is so vast that convincing people to pay attention to the right abstractions rather than to the evidence of their (more than five) senses is pretty much the only way to keep the circus running. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt102162", "title": "Re: Magic Monday Greetings!", "date": "2017-12-26 09:45 am", "user": "ferngladefarm.blogspot.com.au", "content": "Hi John Michael,<br/><br/>Many thanks for the considered reply. Your reply reminded me that years ago we spoke about hexes and the inevitable blow-back from those. With that in mind I have two questions:<br/>1) Do you feel that there is blow back building and is it an expression of the present disequilibrium? and<br/>2) Other than being the change you want to see in the world, are there any other effective counter spells I could employ in my toolkit?<br/><br/>Sorry, that was actually three questions! I am occasionally very cheeky! Hehe!<br/><br/>Cheers<br/><br/>Chris", "replies": [{"id": "cmt108306", "title": "Re: Magic Monday Greetings!", "date": "2017-12-27 12:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, yes, and the regular practice of any magical or spiritual technique that puts you into harmony with the natural world. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt115218", "title": "Re: Magic Monday Greetings!", "date": "2017-12-27 02:27 am", "user": "ferngladefarm.blogspot.com.au", "content": "Hi John Michael,<br/><br/>Thank you for the reply and so be it.<br/><br/>Harmony is a curious word, but yeah I hear you. If nature has taught me anything it is that it can be simultaneously beautiful and terrifying among other attributes and experiences. Last night one of my dogs killed a fox cub. It was the second in as many weeks. The fox cub is now feeding the worms, which in turn feed the soil, which in turn feeds the plants that the many marsupials that live here feed on. The fox cub would have taken a few of the young marsupials (not the older ones) in its time. Such circularity is not lost on me and well, I can see that I'm not apart from that loop. It is pretty awesome to contemplate and know that sooner or later your lucky numbers will turn up.<br/><br/>Chris"}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt91154", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-25 11:27 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm having a difficult time visualizing the organization and interrelationships among the various planes.  I work better with diagrams and mathematics, unfortunately.  Could you give a quick overview and/or point to some diagrams summarizing the structure?  I'm also about a third the way into _The Cosmic Doctrine_ and I'm afraid I don't have a much clearer picture than when I first started.<br/><br/>And thank you for this open occult question session today.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt92434", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 12:20 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "When you read <i>The Cosmic Doctrine</i>, do you take the time to imagine each visual image as clearly as possible before you go on? That's essential to working with the text; as the book says, it's there to train the mind rather than informing it. As for the planes, you may be overthinking it. The planes relate to one another the way that the different sections of the electromagnetic spectrum relate to one another: they're all present in the same space, but you tune into one or another at a time. There are various ways of dividing the spectrum, but they all fit into a continuum reaching from pure spirit to solid matter; it's just a matter of where you draw the dividing lines. "}]}, {"id": "cmt91410", "title": "Association of elements with directions", "date": "2017-12-25 11:28 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John, and thanks for this opportunity to ask questions.<br/><br/>How important is the association of the elements with the four cardinal points? Traditional Golden Dawn has Air, Fire, Water and Earth in the East, South, West and North respectively. However, other systems associate them differently, e.g. inverting Water and Earth. Similarly, some people invert the associations with the tarot suits, so Air/Swords and Fire/Wands are often coupled instead: Air/Wands and Fire/Swords.<br/><br/>What are the bases in occult theory for these permutations? Is it just 'what works' or is there a logic that can be explained?<br/><br/>Gigoachef", "replies": [{"id": "cmt92690", "title": "Re: Association of elements with directions", "date": "2017-12-26 12:21 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's more or less arbitrary; different systems use different correspondences. What's important is to use the specific set that goes with whatever magical tradition you're working with, as it'll have been chosen for good reasons, and unintelligent tinkering with established systems is one of the primary sources of failure in magical practice these days. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt118290", "title": "Re: Association of elements with directions", "date": "2017-12-27 03:49 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, John.<br/><br/>-Gigoachef"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt91666", "title": "Incarnations and Pan", "date": "2017-12-25 11:47 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, Happy Holidays and a Merry Ole Magic Monday Sans Christmas Music Treacle -<br/><br/>(from Will M)<br/><br/>Two questions - you mentioned that, according to Druidic perspective, a soul must corporeally incarnate until every human experience is indeed experienced, this before the soul can move on to higher realms. I'm wondering tho if by Druidic perspective a soul by dint of desire and the will-power to see it through, can skip certain incarnations, can spiritually elevate itself in one incarnation so that other incarnations do not have to be experienced. Or is it absolutely necessary that the soul experience everything no matter how elevated it might become in any one incarnation? <br/><br/>Also, going back to your Death of God post - though the god Pan \"died\" with the advent of Christ, would it be fair to say that Pan really took a back seat to the New God in terms of immediacy and power? After all, people have continued to see and experience Pan albeit in isolated cases. I imagine that Christ will continue to exist similarly, with a depleted immediacy and power, perhaps to be integrated into a new god and religion. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt92946", "title": "Re: Incarnations and Pan", "date": "2017-12-26 12:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The teaching doesn't say that you have to experience all things in every incarnation.  Since you don't know what you've already experienced in previous incarnations, don't worry about it. If you've reached the point that you want to elevate yourself spiritually to what the Druid teachings call Gwynfydd, the luminous life, then you've probably already had the experiences you need -- otherwise you'd be longing for those, or for the things that would bring those about, rather than aspiring to Gwynfydd. <br/><br/>The one very notable exception to this rule is if you're trying to attain spiritual elevation in an attempt to run away from unsolved issues in your life. That doesn't work. If you're longing for Gwynfydd because you think it's easier than dealing with relationship problems, or your difficulties with work or money, or what have you, stop and deal with those first. It's when you've experienced what incarnate life has to offer and are ready to go on to other things that you're ready for Gwynfydd. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt110866", "title": "Re: Incarnations and Pan", "date": "2017-12-27 01:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "From Alexander Marcus<br/><br/>Can pursuing Gwynfydd when not yet ready for it precipitate being \"forced\" to have what incarnate experiences one still needs to have?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt114962", "title": "Re: Incarnations and Pan", "date": "2017-12-27 02:02 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yep. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt91922", "title": "Druidry and Daoism", "date": "2017-12-26 12:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, this is Bogatyr.<br/><br/>As I’ve mentioned before om WoG, I’m from the same town as Iolo Morganwg. I’ve walked the same woods and fields that he knew, and drunk in the same taverns.  I read the Mabinogion over and over when I was younger. The Druidry that you’ve presented in your recent blogging resonates with me, and I’d like to explore it further. <br/><br/>However, as you ay have gathered, i live now in China. My Green Wizard, learn-a-skill-for-decline plan is focussed on learning Chinese Medicine, specifically acupuncture and qigong. The forms of taijiquan and yiquan that I’m learning include a lot of neigong. So, I’m doing a lot of energy work in the Chinese tradition.<br/><br/>To what extent are these compatible, given all that you’ve said previously about combining Western and Eastern energetic systems? (What would be great would be a handy guide to what’s safe, what’s not, and where to progress with caution - but that’s too much to ask!)<br/><br/>Would the OBOD course be OK (safe?) for someone doing a lot of neigong?<br/><br/>Thanks for the work you’re doing, and thanls in advance for any thoughts you may have on this topic!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt93202", "title": "Re: Druidry and Daoism", "date": "2017-12-26 12:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know a lot about the current OBOD curriculum; the original version doesn't conflict with taijiquan and qigong, but I can't guarantee that the newer version won't. Since you're studying a coherent, effective system of spiritual training, I'd encourage you to stick to that when it comes to practices, and pursue Druidry only as a philosophy and a spirituality. The basic rule of thumb is <i>don't mix energy work</i>. Since Iolo didn't teach any energy work -- that all entered the Druid Revival tradition after his time -- you're on pretty safe ground there, and since there are some fairly intriguing parallels between Druidry and Taoism, you ought to have fun becoming a Taoist Druid. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt100882", "title": "Re: Druidry and Daoism", "date": "2017-12-26 05:42 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes, I’ve noticed certain resonances, I mentioned recently on your blog my belief that there was once a continuity, a spectrum, of beliefs running from the Atlantic to the Pacific, and I suspect that there’s much to be discovered here. I wonder to what extent working with qi on the one hand, and nwyfre with the other, will turn out to be looking at the same thing through different filters...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt108562", "title": "Re: Druidry and Daoism", "date": "2017-12-27 12:30 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, very much so -- but that doesn't mean the techniques are compatible. Even within Chinese internal arts, there are things you don't combine; I was warned by my sifu in Seattle never to combine the kind of taijiquan and neigung we were doing, for example, with iron palm training, because people who do that combination get sick and die young. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt93714", "title": "Protection against accidental curses", "date": "2017-12-26 12:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,<br/><br/>I have two friends whose family member - let's call her Jill - likes to give them advice in the form of implications:<br/><br/>\"If you do very slightly risky thing X, bad thing Y will happen.\"<br/><br/>This probably sounds very reasonable, until you learn that:<br/><br/>1. Most people who have done thing X in the past did not suffer from bad thing Y.<br/>2. When one of my friends does thing X, bad thing Y usually does happen.<br/><br/>It took my friends years to realize that the reason Jill's words so often came true was not because of her special insight, but because she would say it with such conviction that the statement accidentally became a curse. Both of them tried talking to her about it, but she insists that she means well, and she doesn't even believe in magic. Because her intentions are mostly good, they do not want to cut her out of their lives.<br/><br/>Can you recommend any reliable resources where my friends can learn:<br/><br/>1. how to protect themselves against any further curses of this type?<br/>2. how to cancel any existing curses which have not yet come true?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt97298", "title": "Re: Protection against accidental curses", "date": "2017-12-26 03:27 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends very much on what kind of magic your friends are willing to do. I'm far from certain the curses are as accidental as you suggest, though -- the habit of saying something like that with conviction and intensity of focus is not exactly innocent, you know. "}, {"id": "cmt101650", "title": "Re: Protection against accidental curses", "date": "2017-12-26 07:02 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, of course, I forgot to specify my friend's attitude towards magic.<br/><br/>Both of them are comfortable with things such as creative visualization, candle magic, Wicca-style spellcasting, magical baths, natural magic. They would probably be fine with amulets, but I don't think they have sufficient magical skill to successfully create one. However, neither of them is comfortable working with deities and other spiritual beings, so something like the LBRP is probably out.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt108818", "title": "Re: Protection against accidental curses", "date": "2017-12-27 12:45 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, in that case, have them take a black candle, write the words of Jill's curse on the candle with a sharp object, and then light the candle saying, \"As this creature of wax dwindles, so will your curse, Jill. When the candle is gone the curse will be gone.\" (This can be gussied up, turned into a poem or chant, or what have you.) Then burn the candle all the way down to the socket; any leftover wax should be gathered up and put piece by piece into the melted wax of a burning pillar candle, and allowed to burn up. After they do this working, have them take a protective bath, washing down from head to toe -- the old classic hoodoo bath of cold water with salt, vinegar, and a teaspoon of cayenne pepper is good for this. Some of the water should be taken out and thrown on the roots of a strong tree immediately after the bath. <br/><br/>Oh, and the next time Jill says something like that, they should respond at once by saying, \"If you make negative predictions like that, the bad things you predict will come to you instead.\" They should go on to say that Every. Single. Time. she engages in her habit of cursing in their presence, until she gets so sick of hearing it that she stops. <br/><br/>This is not a minor thing. Jill's behavior is one of the things that ordinary people (as distinct from theologians and inquisitors) used to mean when they used the word \"witch.\" "}]}]}, {"id": "cmt93970", "title": "Possession", "date": "2017-12-26 01:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, this is Bogatyr again. Thanks for the reply upthread. I also have another question, namely: where does possession fit into the system of Druidry? (If it does at all).<br/><br/>I ask because the tradition of the Mari Lwyd endures in my hometown: a mare’s skull on a pole, with a shroud-like white sheet covering the bearer. A few years back, I was part of the group taking the Mari around the local taverns and was under the sheet, carrying her, when we went into one of the older pubs (which, yes, Iolo would have known). I can only describe what happened next as a case of possession.<br/><br/>Much like I’ve read about hypnotism, my mind was present and I felt like I could stop if I wanted to. Yet, it definitely felt like I was off to one side while a different intelligence ran the meat-puppet for a while. It was a *very* mischievous, fundamentally well-meaning, and slightly naive spirit - and very much a strong-willed personality - ie, the Mari Lwyd. <br/><br/>I never felt in danger, there was never any doubt that the Mari was going to leave after she’d had a bit of fun, and it was really only when I looked back that I understood what has happened.<br/><br/>When I lived in Singapore, I knew tang-kis, the traditional Chinese spirit mediums, who act as hosts for folk deities. Their experience is different, however: as with voudun, the possessed are not aware of events while they’re being “ridden”, and have no subsequent memory of what happened.<br/><br/>Where does all of this fit in with Druidry?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt97554", "title": "Re: Possession", "date": "2017-12-26 03:29 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. Remember that Druidry is a very diverse movement, and has a complex and often contested relationship with Celtic folk custom! It might make more sense, rather than \"where does all this fit in with Druidry,\" to ask \"Where does this fit in with my Druidry?\" and find your own answer to that question. "}]}, {"id": "cmt94226", "title": "Yay Magic Monday!", "date": "2017-12-26 01:09 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks so much for Magic Monday, JMG.  I learn so, so much from the questions and your answers.<br/><br/>I don’t know if this question is strictly of the occult variety, but have you an opinion of the practice of ho’oponopono?  It’s apparently a Hawaiian practice, modified by Westerners (that makes me a bit wary) where the practitioner focuses their attention on the intended recipient either in person or not, and says “I’m sorry.  Please forgive me.  I love you.  Thank you.”  Numerous times.  The aim being to heal the relationship.<br/><br/>Any thoughts?<br/><br/>Appreciatively,<br/>OtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt97810", "title": "Re: Yay Magic Monday!", "date": "2017-12-26 03:31 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm. That could either be really healing or really creepy, depending on the underlying intention. Don't do it without getting the permission of the target first. "}]}, {"id": "cmt94482", "title": "SoP", "date": "2017-12-26 01:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John, and thank you for hosting this forum. I’ve been working through the Druid Magic Handbook and have just reached the seventh gate/ complete SoP ritual. I’ve lived in the Central Valley of California nearly my whole life and have formatted the ritual to associate the mountains in the east (vibrating the word “Sierra”) with Air, the deserts to the south (vibrating the words “Sonora-Mojave”) with fire, the ocean to the west (vibrating the word “Pacifica”) with water, and the forest to the north ( vibrating the word “sequoia”) with earth. The fifth, sixth, and seventh gates ive left how you have them in the book minus any mention of the welsh gods.  I’m early in my practice (3 months) but want to know if my approach is too generic. Am I going to have diminished effects by not calling upon the gods and is my association with places to the elements not appropriate? I use these places because they have been a big part of my spiritual life and lead me to a pursuit of a nature religion. The results are pleasant but tepid, as expected in the early phases of work. Let me know if I have misappropriated the ritual. Thanks! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt98066", "title": "Re: SoP", "date": "2017-12-26 03:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you're probably going to have diminished effects by not calling on gods, but if that's what you prefer to do, then them's the breaks. It really is up to you. "}]}, {"id": "cmt94994", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 01:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the Sphere of Protection, does the tracing of the banishing form of an elemental symbol erase the original tracing, or renew it?<br/><br/>Is there a reason for the particular order of the different rotation directions in the SoP Circulation of Light?<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt98322", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 03:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "(a) neither one. It banishes, according to your intention. <br/><br/>(b) yes. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt99602", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 04:29 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I phrased my question poorly--I meant: do I visualize the lines that I originally traced dissapearing as I trace them in reverse? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt109074", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 12:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. The lines are strengthened by being drawn over again in the other way. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt96018", "title": "Unlearning, mourning the loss of a living mind/earth", "date": "2017-12-26 03:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Howdy, <br/><br/>I've been struggling with parsing my training as a \"rational\" and scientific thinker from my early childhood and into young adulthood with the imperative to honor the living earth as a conscious entity. I cringe and balk at some ideas of magic and occultism, most of it scares or doesn't interest me — though I do have a strong interest in druidry and local environmental knowledge. However, I want to explore the spiritual aspects of the earth and how our species can be a co-creator in the spirit of our regions. I want to reconcile these with my (forced) training into the dominant scientific-rational-technological culture. In a way, I sometimes feel like I'll never truly unlearn this culture and that I'll be stuck in a material, dead universe. Sorry I'm throwing out a lot of things here,<br/><br/>So I suppose my question is — how long did it take you to unlearn or transition from being resistant to magic, druidry, spirituality et al? To a place where it began to feel natural with meaning and purpose in your life? Are there any books that help along with this process of transition into intuitive/spiritual/magical knowledge and practice? Books that perhaps sound \"more sane\" to someone straight out of the West?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt98578", "title": "Re: Unlearning, mourning the loss of a living mind/earth", "date": "2017-12-26 03:41 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm probably not the right person to ask about this. From earliest childhood, I felt that the dead world of matter that I was taught about by parents, teachers, and the media was a lie. As a child I was fascinated by anything and everything that strayed outside the materialist consensus -- I was an expert on werewolf trivia at age ten, for example, and crazy in love with fantasy fiction -- and when I found my first manual of training in operative magic, I felt as though I'd come out of a dark cold room into sunlight and springtime. <br/><br/>I'd make two suggestions. The first is to put some serious time into reading mythologies and folktales instead of modern \"serious\" books. The second is to consider taking up some kind of magical practice. Actions speak louder than words, in this as in other contexts; it can be very frightening to actually do the work, but that's the best way I know of to shake off the \"mind-forg'd manacles\" that Blake wrote about. "}, {"id": "cmt106514", "title": "Re: Unlearning, mourning the loss of a living mind/earth", "date": "2017-12-26 11:26 pm", "user": "smj", "content": "Hi there<br/><br/>I'm also highly trained as a rational scientific thinker (mechanical engineering PhD), and I went through a conflict that seems similar to yours. The first thing that really started the shift for me was when I realised that you cannot prove non-existence. This is the case because each time you fail to detect the presence of something, there is always, always the possibility that there's something wrong with your equipment or methodology.<br/><br/>Once I realised this to be true, I realised that it is impossible to know how much you don't know. And then it became clear that many of my attitudes, justified and encouraged by the current scientific orthodoxy, were in fact prejudices. How do you know that the earth is not a conscious entity? There is nothing to prove this to be the case. If you want to apply rationalism strictly rigourously, all you can say is that you haven't yet found any conclusive evidence of the earth being a conscious entity. True science admits when it doesn't know.<br/><br/>As for magic and occultism, don't worry too much about it. You'll come to it in your own way, which won't necessarily be in this lifetime (is there any conclusive proof that reincarnation doesn't happen?). Being scared of it is a perfectly reasonable response, just make sure that your fear of it: a) doesn't prevent you from considering the possibility that it works; and b) makes you treat it with respect.<br/><br/>Hope this helps.<br/><br/>SMJ", "edit_time": "2017-12-26 11:27 pm (UTC)"}]}, {"id": "cmt96274", "title": "Ancestor worship gone bad", "date": "2017-12-26 03:18 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG, please accept my best wishes for 2018!<br/><br/> A couple of posts ago, in response to a comment on the subject of veneration of ancestors, you mentioned that it had in at least one case degenerated into a very negative  affair.<br/><br/>I have a sketchy idea of how the Inca of Peru invented a religion of the ancestors that sucked up a huge portion of the productive land for the ‘support’ of the royal dead, which effectively  evicted the living and required every new monarch to go out conquering the world just to get a post-mortem ‘livelihood’.  And I have come across oblique indications that something of the sort probably happened in pagan Europe. Can you fill us in on some more detail, or direct me where to look for such information? <br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt98834", "title": "Re: Ancestor worship gone bad", "date": "2017-12-26 03:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of a good book on the subject, but basically what happened was this. There was a very old set of spiritual practices by which individuals would step outside of the cycle of reincarnation for a time, to serve as spiritual guardians of a place or a community. It involved intensive spiritual practice, followed by a deliberate death in an earth-sheltered stone tomb (to keep the subtle body from being disrupted by sunlight). The long barrows of northwestern Europe were places where this was done. Only a few people in any generation did this; the others simply died and were reborn in the usual way. <br/><br/>Later on, as societies became more hierarchical and materialistic, members of the ruling classes started to use a variant of this to try to escape death. That's when you went to individual burials in round barrows and the like, with grave treasures and the like. Offerings of various kinds were used to replace the spiritual disciplines. That's what became standard practice in Egypt and other places -- the king would be mummified and buried in a stone tomb, and offerings would be used to nourish his spirit. Of course the problem was that you ended up with more and more of the economy being diverted to the support of the dead, resulting in a galaxy of economic and political troubles. <br/><br/>The backlash happened in different ways in different places, but that's why in classical times the dead were burnt, not buried, and why Christian practice into early modern times was to bury the dead in relatively shallow, unsheltered graves until the flesh rotted, and then heap the bones in an ossuary. The result in all cases was to make the Second Death happen promptly, so that the dead didn't hang around and make nuisances of themselves. <br/><br/>The final, decadent version of the old tradition is dimly recalled in the legends of vampirism. The would-be vampire tried a do-it-yourself version of the old tradition, for the wholly selfish purpose of dodging death as long as possible. Predation on the living took the place of offerings. It rarely worked for long, not least because people figured out how to mess with it.  It was an ugly ending for what had started out as a profound and very positive spiritual technology. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt118546", "title": "Re: Ancestor worship gone bad", "date": "2017-12-27 05:20 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was rereading one of Lynda Robinson's Lord Meren mysteries set in the time of King Tutankhamen when it occurred to me that tomb robbers may have served an important, if unrecognized, role in the Egyptian economy by getting some of the treasure back into circulation. <br/><br/>Rita"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt99090", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 04:17 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are your thoughts on meme magic? Mere psychological warfare, or something greater still?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt109330", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 12:48 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on who's doing it and what kind of magical technique they include in their memetic work. I do a lot with memes, as you may have noticed, and I vary from purely psychological methods to other things. "}]}, {"id": "cmt99858", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 04:36 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ray Wharton.<br/><br/>I Just got back from three weeks out on the Dineta herding sheep. Most of my waking day was spent wandering in the dry gulches following sheep or burying apricot pits. During that time I spent a lot of time reflecting on spiritual matters, specifically ovate grade meditations from CGD. Two highlights include a comparason of the serenity prayer to the three rays of light, and a meditation on water while watching sheep flow from gully to gully. I am going back for another three week spell as soon as a few responsibilities in Cortez are done.<br/><br/>Upon returning to a artificial house in a bright lit trailer park, with TV viewing roommates I am sickly crippled. Its like a tea totaler trying to go shot for shot with a career alcoholic; my resistance is atrophied. During the day time here I am expected to urinate inside of the structure like a dumb puppy, gross.<br/><br/>Anyway, the question. I have also been thinking a lot about the planes and what sorts of entities... how to say, have their being concentrated in a roughly limited section of the planes. How strange, among embodied beings, is the human connection to the intellectual plane? There are some many intelligent patterns, from the patterns in eroding hill sides, to the construction or behavior of biotic forms that it is clear the intellectual plane is doing just fine embodying itself with out us.<br/><br/>I read an interesting book out there, The Spell of the Sensuous, it was pretty good exploration of why Western civilization is so obsessed with living in a dead universe. The writer focused on our use of an alphabetic writing system, and how it affects our relation to others; he intentionally stretched the point too far, that it causes us to relate to ideas that seem unchanging, written and fixed, and inspired a special focus on ideas over sensation or feelings. <br/><br/>But, this isn't a book review, the point I am trying to circle in on is that it occurred to me that writing, and certain other popular mental activities of recent millennia, including the fancier forms of maths and such, have opened us to encounter a range of entities concentrated around the ideal plane like Australia encountering cane toads and cats, thereby causing a radical disturbance and re-balancing, which is a very messy and costly process, rich with sad happenings.<br/><br/>I have come to suspect that I became sensitive to the intellectual plane early and acutely, but that it is actually kinda a rough neighborhood to find oneself in, filled with Ideas which would be very pleased to enslave me and set me to work materializing them on one form or another. For instance, I have explored the arithmetic of the Fibonacci numbers for hundreds of hours, maybe thousands, and in many ways it has been a healthy relationship, at least healthy enough that I an glad to continue it, and has taught me beautiful things and shaped me in beautiful ways. Other thoughts have grabbed me less constructively, and in order to realize anything in my life I am needing to fend on these courting Ideas, that I can focus.<br/><br/>At the moment I am all but possessed by thoughts of building Guastavino Vaulting for a cellar. Seed saving. Sheep Herding. Flute music. Magic. Dry land farming. Leather working. A lot of these are from denser planes, but I am coming to terms with the fact that my interests have their own interests in me.<br/><br/>The beings I am meeting in magic are those I have long known with out knowing that, to be exact with words, they knew me. What should I be wary of as certain relationships transform from I-It to _I-you, what is the hazards of that transition?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt109586", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 12:53 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Deal with them the same way you'd deal with people you know, and you should be fine. Maintain healthy boundaries, maintain your own center, and choose your relationships rather than having others choose them for you:  all the usual stuff. "}]}, {"id": "cmt100626", "title": "\"Fortune Cards\"", "date": "2017-12-26 05:27 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My husband got me a set of Madame Endora's Fortune Cards for an Alban Arthuan gift.  I had never touched a tarot deck or \"fortune cards\" or a Ouija board or anything like that.  Nor had I ever had my fortune told in any way.  I hadn't ever thought of doing it either, but decided to read the directions included and try it.  I was really shocked that the cards were applicable to my life and to the question I asked.  I later did two other readings that also seemed very accurate.<br/><br/>What, or who, actually provides these answers?  I hadn't expected this kind of result.  I thought the person doing the reading would have to have a certain level of skill or ability that I'm pretty sure I don't have.  I didn't even know the meanings of the cards before I did it.  After the first one I did, I actually went through the deck to check the other cards and make sure that it wasn't the case where any card would have worked.  There were definitely cards that would not have made sense for my life or the question I asked.<br/><br/>What kind of being answered, and can he or she be trusted to be honest?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt109842", "title": "Re: \"Fortune Cards\"", "date": "2017-12-27 12:57 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You are doing the answering. Divination is a way you bring to the surface the things you know subconsciously but not consciously. When you shuffle the cards and cut the deck, micromovements of your hands guided by your subconscious mind control which cards are waiting to be dealt out. <br/><br/>All this is perfectly natural. Some people have to develop skill with divination cards, but others have a natural talent for it, and the fact that you evidently have such a talent is something to celebrate, not something to be afraid of! You now have an ability that will help you guide yourself and others through the complexities of everyday life. Have fun with it, keep a journal of your readings, and use your talent wisely, and it'll bring you many blessings. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt117522", "title": "Re: \"Fortune Cards\"", "date": "2017-12-27 06:28 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for the reply!  That's a relief since I know that I'm honest and trustworthy.  :-)  Although I guess that the danger could be in what I really, truly don't know, even subconsciously.<br/><br/>BTW, this is Garden Housewife.  I had to post as anonymous, and forgot to add that on the last comment."}]}]}, {"id": "cmt101138", "title": "Magic Monday Questions", "date": "2017-12-26 06:09 am", "user": "marcu", "content": "Dear Mr. Greer, <br/><br/>As is tradition for me at this time of year I'm reviewing the past year and trying to structure my plans for the next. As such your Magical Monday comes at a very opportune time since I have a few questions that I would appreciate your insight on. <br/>-Do you have any thoughts or recommendations on studying the magical Cabala (Paths of Wisdom) and Druidry (Druidry Handbook) at the same time? Or would you recommend doing one before the other? <br/><br/>-In the Druidry Handbook is the intention to pick one of the paths or to pursue all of the paths concurrently? <br/><br/>-As I understand your books are aimed at students who intend self study, but especially for the magical Cabala, do you have any recommendations on finding like minded individuals to study with or to find teachers to assist with questions? <br/><br/>Thank you for the opportunity to ask these questions, <br/><br/>Marcu <br/><br/>P.S. I hope everything is on track with The Weird of Hali: Chorazin, I'm really looking forward to the next book! ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt110098", "title": "Re: Magic Monday Questions", "date": "2017-12-27 01:01 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "a) Always, always do one system of magical training at a time.<br/><br/>b) You do all three of them concurrently. <br/><br/>c) If you're working with <i>The Druidry Handbook</i>, the Ancient Order of Druids in America at www.aoda.org is the place to go -- the book is a study guide to AODA's approach to Druidry. <br/><br/>d) Last I heard, everything's on schedule for Chorazin. I'll be happy to see it in print as well! "}]}, {"id": "cmt101394", "title": "AODA curriculum", "date": "2017-12-26 06:31 am", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Hello JMG,<br/><br/>In a not too distantly past response to a comment on a post over at the other blog, I remember you mentioning that there had been a change in focus of the AODA curriculum that you found unfortunate.<br/><br/>If it is appropriate to comment on here, what changed about it that lessened its usefulness, in your view?<br/><br/>many thanks!<br/>Bonnie", "replies": [{"id": "cmt110354", "title": "Re: AODA curriculum", "date": "2017-12-27 01:03 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The old curriculum had a set of seven spirals that worked very well. When we upgraded the curriculum in 2010, I think it was, we replaced that with something more freeform, which didn't work anything like as well. Since I retired before the next curriculum revision, I didn't have a chance to revise things again -- if I had, we'd have gone back to the spirals. ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt111122", "title": "Re: AODA curriculum", "date": "2017-12-27 01:28 am", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Thanks!"}]}]}, {"id": "cmt102674", "title": "metal in body", "date": "2017-12-26 10:26 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(rabtter)<br/><br/>Does having mercury tooth fillings or a metal greenfield filter in an artery affect etheric energy around your body?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt110610", "title": "Re: metal in body", "date": "2017-12-27 01:04 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't noticed any effect from tooth fillings. Since I haven't encountered the other situation, I can't speak to it from experience. "}]}, {"id": "cmt102930", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 11:03 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have loads of question stored up so feel free not to answer them all and sorry I'm late!<br/> <br/>How would you know if you’re seeking Gwynfydd to get away from unresolved issues in your life or because you’re ready for it? I have loads of mess in my life that I know was mostly caused by my personality and upbringing and I’m working on fixing that and magic is helping. I’m also just really curious about Gwynfydd. But another part of me would really like to not be a social primate anymore at all, so that’s kind of a motive of wanting to escape. If you have mixed motives what does that mean? <br/><br/>On a related note, I’ve read people saying that aiming at self-improvement is a distraction from achieving enlightenment and can get in the way of it – that’s it’s just a game the ego plays. I think this is more Eastern, buddhist-influenced mysticism than the tradition you come from. Is that attitude a rejection of the world as it is, an attempt to stop people from confusing morality with spirituality, or something else? <br/><br/>Also, I read a blog by a girl who claims to be enlightened and described a state of what feels like love all the time. But then she said that years later she’d discovered that there are things beyond that and she’s not in that zone anymore. Is there some ‘mystical’ experience that’s the source of the idea that God is love? <br/><br/>And what is the truth about that? I come across Christians, New Age types, Buddhists and lefties who all share this idea. Usually what they mean by love is basically compassion although they all have different names for it. Christians on a forum I’m on insist that agape is the ultimate reality, Buddhist-influenced types say it’s loving kindness, lefties say it’s solidarity and unity. Leaving aside that whenever I get to know such people I usually find they’re among the nastiest you’ll ever meet… are they right on some level? I’m extremely disagreeable by temperament so maybe it just grates on me that my natural disposition is apparently so un-God-like!<br/> <br/>The Christians tell me that what they mean is that something like agape is the closest reflection at the human level of the divine spark. But then they believe in an omniscient, omnipotent, omnibenevolent creator god too, which I don’t, but I don’t want to discard everything they say either. I’ve been reading Eliphas Levi and I think to the extent Jesus existed he was probably a pretty advanced initiate. And he was the one who started the whole ‘God is Love’ thing as far as I know. I don’t think anyone ever said Zeus was love.<br/><br/>Thank you,<br/><br/>Dot.<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt111378", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 01:28 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Mixed motives are pretty standard among human beings! If you're making an honest effort to deal with your troubles rather than just turning your back on them, you're going about things the right way and will attain Gwynfydd without any undue delay. <br/><br/>Self-improvement doesn't have to be an ego game. It can also be a constructive and compassionate response to the experience of living in the world. The pursuit of enlightenment, for that matter, very often gets turned into an ego game! It's important not to confuse morality with spirituality, sure, but that doesn't mean morality is irrelevant -- far from it. <br/><br/>The \"God is Love\" notion strikes me as profoundly unbalanced. Why not \"God is Justice\" or \"God is Wisdom\" or even \"God is Life\"? For that matter, why does the religion that insists most loudly that \"God is Love\" so often get so frantically bent out of shape when it comes to the normal, natural, healthy physical expression of love, i.e., sex? I think there's something very out of kilter there. "}]}, {"id": "cmt103186", "title": "Prayer", "date": "2017-12-26 11:34 am", "user": "orathbone", "content": "Hi JMG, you mention you use ‘prayer’ as a means of communication with higher powers. Could you go into some greater detail on this? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt111634", "title": "Re: Prayer", "date": "2017-12-27 01:32 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's very simple. Talk to a deity the way you would talk to anyone you respect, and then listen for an answer. Regular practice is essential, and so is the right attitude -- you're wasting your time if you do this to try to force a deity to prove to you that he or she exists, for example. If you approach regular prayer the way you'd approach a regular conversation with someone you respect profoundly, and let the experience and the relationship deepen, the practice itself will teach you what you need to do. "}]}, {"id": "cmt103442", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 12:29 pm", "user": "jbucks", "content": "Apologies if this comes too late. I have very little experience with magic, I recently bought a copy of the Druid Magic Handbook and I've read Mystery Teachings of the Living Earth, but because of life events I don't have the time to do it yet as properly as you suggested in the introduction to the former book, so I'm holding off until I do. <br/><br/>Part of the reason for that is I spend what free time I do get learning to write music - which leads me to my question: I quite naively wonder what connections exist between playing musical instruments, writing or improvising music, and magic? Are there ways to connect somehow the learning of both simultaneously? <br/><br/>There is something that just draws me in with trying to compose music that is hard to explain - your comment in a reply to something I wrote in another thread about 'music as a way of knowing' comes close.", "edit_time": "2017-12-26 12:35 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt111890", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 01:33 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not everyone is meant to be an operative mage. You may be meant to be a musician and composer instead. Music (like all the arts) can also be pursued as a deep and intense spiritual practice; if you pay close attention to how your music affects your state of consciousness and that of your listeners, it very quickly approximates magic. That may well be your proper path. "}]}, {"id": "cmt103954", "title": "Enchantment and equipment", "date": "2017-12-26 01:11 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Archdruid;<br/><br/>I have several questions, but they are all related. So perhaps they are permissible as one?<br/><br/>Suppose one would enchant a standing stone with the DMH ritual, then later the same stone would be enchanted with, let's say, a DOGD ritual. Would this have adverse effects? Is enchantment 'stacking' inherently a bad thing, or are some systems compatible? Can one adjust the initial enchantment to accept later input from a different system?<br/><br/>In the same vein, can a wand, or sickle, be used for various traditions of magic, or is it best enchanted and used for a single tradition only?<br/><br/>Finally, suppose two people in the same house are working through the DOGD curriculum together, what implements can be shared? I know the divination tools shouldn't be touched by anyone else. But can they both use the same altar?<br/><br/>Yours in Druidry,<br/>Brigyn", "replies": [{"id": "cmt112146", "title": "Re: Enchantment and equipment", "date": "2017-12-27 01:38 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "a) Don't mix enchantments. If you enchant a stone with one set of energies using one ritual, the only way you want to reenchant it is to use the same ritual over again to strengthen the force. Otherwise you just end up with a muddle. <br/><br/>b) If the wand or sickle is enchanted, it needs to be used in the tradition in which it was enchanted, and there only. If not, it can be used more generally. (I have an earthenware cup that's been used in rituals in more than a dozen different magical systems, but it's never been enchanted or consecrated.) <br/><br/>c) The altar and all its furnishings can be shared. The Druid Wands and, when you get to the Druid Grade, the working tools need to be individual. "}]}, {"id": "cmt104210", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 01:13 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John Michael,<br/><br/>Thanks for this opportunity to ask questions!<br/><br/>I am thinking about the fact that you wrote in the Galabes: \"“The whole of magical theory and practice,” the great English magical teacher Dion Fortune wrote, “turns on two points—autosuggestion and the astral light.”\" and the post on surfing astral light is probably my favourite, and I was hoping to see the second one about the other point. <br/><br/>I am working with Bardon's system and the theoretical explanation of unconscious is that it's opposite and enemy of conscious mind. This approach (my sub-conscious is an enemy) does yeld useful results and I cleared a lot of negative behavioral and mental pattern using Bardon's methods. <br/><br/>But still, I am noticing that unconscious have a lots of positive aspects too. What are other approches to conceptualize unconcious mind from occult perspective? <br/><br/>Changeling", "replies": [{"id": "cmt112402", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 01:42 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Most 20th century occult systems deal with the subconscious mind. I don't find it at all useful to see the subconscious as the enemy of the conscious mind -- if that's the case, you've got major problems! Rather, it's simply the mind we all inherit from our primate ancestry: a very well adapted social primate mind, dealing somewhat awkwardly with having a cerebral cortex and a complex conscious mind loaded on top of it. You can establish cordial relations with it, train it, listen to it when you should, overrride it when that's the better option -- it's very much as though you have a large pet dog who's been very badly trained and has bad habits, but is still willing to learn. "}]}, {"id": "cmt104466", "title": "Rosicrucianism?", "date": "2017-12-26 01:50 pm", "user": "smwils1", "content": "JMG,<br/>the Rosicrucians meet monthly here in Lexington, and that made me interested in them. However, in reading their literature, I've found some things that concern me about them (possibly thinking that the planes are not discrete--overconfidence in the ability to change the world, endorsements, etc.) and was wanting your opinion or experience of the Rosicrucians (AMORC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt112658", "title": "Re: Rosicrucianism?", "date": "2017-12-27 01:43 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't have a lot of experience with them, but they've always struck me as Occultism Lite. Still, your mileage may vary. "}]}, {"id": "cmt104722", "title": "A change of tone", "date": "2017-12-26 01:58 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OK, this one's cheating because it's not Monday and it's not about magic. So, I'm not expecting a reply. But.<br/><br/>JMG, it seems to me that your voice (in written form) has changed since you hung up the Big Archdruid Hat. It seems to be a bit more emotional, and rather earthier, than when you were speaking ex cathedra, as it were.<br/><br/>Is it just me? Or do you actually feel freer to use a more personal voice than you did before?<br/><br/>Cheers,<br/><br/>Bogatyr", "replies": [{"id": "cmt112914", "title": "Re: A change of tone", "date": "2017-12-27 01:44 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Bogatyr, no, you're quite correct. Back when I was Grand Panjandrum of AODA I always had to keep in mind that whatever I said would reflect on the large public Druid order I headed. Since I stepped down, that hasn't been the case, and I can relax and unbelt a bit. "}]}, {"id": "cmt105234", "title": "polytheism", "date": "2017-12-26 02:53 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, thanks for hosting and for allowing some trickle over into Tuesday. If this question doesn't make your time cut-off, so be it.<br/><br/>The book of yours that's impacted me most has been A World Full of Gods. Ever since reading it, though, I've been curious about how you personally reconcile the polytheism you describe in that book with your involvement with Freemasons and the Golden Dawn. As far as I understand, both those traditions require acknowledgement of a single supreme being, do they not?<br/><br/>I'm guessing the creation of the Celtic Golden Dawn has had a lot to do with how you've thought through this question. Perhaps there's a 'both/and' answer that I'm unaware of.<br/><br/>- Dylan", "replies": [{"id": "cmt113170", "title": "Re: polytheism", "date": "2017-12-27 01:47 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Every polytheist pantheon I know of has one deity who's more or less the leader of the pack. The phrase \"supreme being\" can be applied just as clearly to such a deity as it can to the sole and exclusive deity of classical monotheism. The Golden Dawn, by the way, doesn't require belief in a supreme being -- it does use Judeo-Christian symbolism, but it also uses symbolism from the ebulliently robust polytheism of ancient Egypt. "}]}, {"id": "cmt105490", "title": "quaternary-plus thinking", "date": "2017-12-26 05:45 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, in The Blood of the Earth you say:<br/><br/>\"The same traditions that taught (and teach) ternary thinking [...] teach more advanced students how to use a range of whole numbers [...] as abstract models of thinking, each in its own proper place and each with its own distinct effects\" (p. 110).<br/><br/>Over a couple of years now, I actually did profit a lot from practicing a variant of what you call ternary thinking, and can only marvel at the further possibilities you mention here. Would you discuss which traditions these are, and do you know of any publicly available literature on quaternary-plus thinking?<br/><br/>Many thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt113426", "title": "Re: quaternary-plus thinking", "date": "2017-12-27 01:49 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The traditions in question are mostly French. The one decent source I know of in English is Mouni Sadhu's strange but useful book <i>The Tarot</i>, which is a very mixed bag but contains a lot of classic occultism. "}]}, {"id": "cmt105746", "title": "Rosi crucianism", "date": "2017-12-26 06:34 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is your take on Rosicrucianism and its practices? I have been reading on it and I must admit I am not particularly impressed with what they have to offer. It seems, to me, more like a kind of moral philosophy with a little bit of occult lore here and there. <br/><br/>They don't seem to give much credence to the much richer non-material universe you have painted lately with nature spirits for example. <br/><br/>Their non-material universe looks like it has been cleared of any spirits leaving the divine quite alone. <br/>Thank you.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt113682", "title": "Re: Rosi crucianism", "date": "2017-12-27 01:50 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That depends on which Rosicrucians you're talking about. There are several dozen organizations that use the term and claim the legacy of the original Rosicrucians, and they have radically different teachings. Which sources have you been reading? ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt116242", "title": "Re: Rosi crucianism", "date": "2017-12-27 03:54 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was referring to the \"Ancien et Mystique Ordre de la Rose Croix (AMORC)\" <br/><br/>Thank you!<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt116754", "title": "Re: Rosi crucianism", "date": "2017-12-27 04:51 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't had a lot of exposure to them, but their teachings have always struck me as Occultism Lite. Still, your mileage may vary. "}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt106002", "title": "Everyday Magic vs \"Temple Magic\"", "date": "2017-12-26 07:07 pm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JAG, hope a Tuesday straggler is okay...<br/><br/>I have noticed that the effectiveness of magical techniques varies pretty widely for me depending on whether I am doing a ritual or a kind of \"ad hoc\" practice in the field.<br/><br/>For example-- a few years ago I started using energetic techniques to accomplish various things. I visualized my central column expanding until it made contact with the person I was looking for (lost cat, girlfriend in a crowded department store, etc.) Or I formed an \"energy ball,\" charged it with a thought, and sent it to the person I wanted to communicate with. My experience has been that these types of techniques work startlingly well the first time I think to try them, then experience a sharp drop off in efficacy, and then rebound to a sort of middling level. <br/><br/>On the other hand, a banishing pentagram ritual is a banishing pentagram ritual, every single time. Do you have any thoughts on why this is?<br/><br/>I was the one that asked about a heptagram ritual above, by the way-- in haste, from a phone,  at the airport. Thanks for your response-- I was thinking of a Hermetic Golden Dawn working. <br/><br/>-Steve Thomas<br/><br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt113938", "title": "Re: Everyday Magic vs \"Temple Magic\"", "date": "2017-12-27 01:51 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "When you do a magical ritual that was created by someone else, and that has been practiced for a while by other people, the egregor -- the subtle energy body of the ritual -- is already established, and your working both draws on it and feeds it. That's a source of stability. When you come up with something from scratch, it has no egregor until your regular practice gives it one, and that's what produces the unsteady effect you've noticed. "}]}, {"id": "cmt106258", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-26 07:50 pm", "user": "smj", "content": "Hello JMG<br/><br/>In your reply to Violet about a buildup of energy in the lower astral plane, you mention that the current buildup is \"unparalleled since the days of a certain legendary and long-drowned civilization\", and the buildup will be discharged by way of natural disasters. Any ideas what caused that previous buildup?<br/><br/>SMJ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt114450", "title": "(no subject)", "date": "2017-12-27 02:00 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The same thing that caused it this time -- the activities of an advanced civilization lethally detached from the natural cycles and realities that supported its existence. "}]}, {"id": "cmt106770", "title": "A comment for those feeling the bad vibes", "date": "2017-12-27 12:07 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may; <br/><br/>The bad vibes have been some of the worst that I've experienced, but I've found myself more resilient to them than at other times in my past.  Why? Well, mostly because of one remarkable herb.<br/><br/>Lemon Balm (Melissa officinalis) was favored by Paracelsus, the great Alchemist and forebear of Western Medicine, who believed it would recharge the mortal oil from which the wick of life burns. More to the point, we can turn to the great English Renaissance herbalist who, in 1652, writes:<br/><br/>\"Seraphio says, it causes the mind and heart to become merry, and revives the heart, faintings and swoonings, especially of such who are overtaken in sleep, and drives away all troublesome cares and thoughts out of the mind, arising from melancholy or black choler; which Avicen also confirms. It is very good to help digestion, and open obstructions of the brain, and hath so much purging quality in it (saith Avicen) as to expel those melancholy vapours from the spirits and blood which are in the heart and arteries, although it cannot do so in other parts of the body. \"<br/><br/>The vague, nighmarish, dark quality to the lower astral makes me think that it has somewhat of a melancholy quality, and so our friend Lemon Balm is helpful for girding the vital spirits and heart.  This I find true in my experience, and from reports of others.  This I combine often with St. John's Wort, which is of ancient repute for clearing away hostile spirits and energies. When I walk at night I carry a spray bottle of St. John's Wort.  If the vibes get spooky I spray the air and it is like sunshine in a bottle; the spirits leave me be.  The contemporary herbalist David Winston combines Lemon Balm and St. John's Wort for the winter blues, and finds this combo highly effective, something I have verified in my practice.<br/>", "replies": [{"id": "cmt115986", "title": "Re: A comment for those feeling the bad vibes", "date": "2017-12-27 02:49 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ray Wharton<br/><br/>Thank you for this comment, happily both are on my seed order list for the coming season, and this stokes my enthusiasm for them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt117266", "title": "Re: A comment for those feeling the bad vibes", "date": "2017-12-27 06:11 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You're so welcome!<br/><br/>~Violet"}]}, {"id": "cmt117010", "title": "Re: A comment for those feeling the bad vibes", "date": "2017-12-27 04:54 am", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I'll keep that in mind. My experience with lemon balm has been mostly in the context of herbal alchemy; if you're doing spagyrics, it's standard in some schools to have lemon balm be the first herb you work with, because it has a curious effect: it makes the mind better able to understand the complex symbolism of alchemy! I'm glad to hear it has other useful properties. ;-) ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt117778", "title": "Re: A comment for those feeling the bad vibes", "date": "2017-12-27 06:34 am", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for this note on Lemon Balm and spagyrics. How utterly fascinating!  I wonder how much that has to do with the fact, validated through recent double-blind placebo controlled studies, that Melissa officinalis generally helps with cognition and may prevent dementia or ameliorate dementia.  Perhaps it helps one to learn a complex system of symbols because it aids in thinking in general?  I'd be rather more delighted though, if its attributes were more in keeping with its own magical intelligence than through some  more mechanistic means.<br/>~Violet"}]}]}]}];